Sensational bowling performance from India. Why need batters to score 400-500 when you don't allow oppositions to score even 200? Jokes apart, except for the first 7-8 overs with the new ball this afternoon, where they wasted and Australia did not take any advantage, they were phenomenal. Mohammed Shami went wicketless but ironically, it was Shami who changed the proceedings. He showed the right lengths to bowl and Bumrah and Umesh duly followed. The duo shared 5 wickets between themselves but when do you a see a spinner take 4 wickets in the first innings - either in or outside India? Bravo R Ashwin, a sensational display, one which Australia would never have expected. They prepared for Bumrah and Shami, but Umesh and Ashwin devoured them.

A sorry batting card for Australia. No David Warner, means that they struggle at the top. And add to it, Steven Smith flops, which means the spinal cord is cut off. Marnus Labuschagne was the only one who showed some resistance in the top half of the batting order and that too, after getting numerous chances. Australia can credit themselves for minimizing the lead though, as at 111/7, from staring at a lead in excess of 120, they have got it down to a shade over 50. Gritty knock from captain Tim Paine amid useful stands with the bowlers.

Hmmm.... a lead of 53! No so great under normal circumstances but when a team has made just under 250, they will take it with open hands. The Indian captain is looking visibly happy and not surprisingly. It is a matter of a watchful 25-30 minutes for tonight before bedding in the whole of tomorrow.

OUT! Caught at slip! Pujara takes a good sharp catch! Umesh bangs it short and outside off. Hazlwood looks to slash at it. It goes off the outside edge and towards first slip. Pujara takes it above his head with a leap. AUSTRALIA HAVE BEEN BOWLED OUT FOR 191!
Umesh Yadav is on!

FOUR! A single is what Paine wanted but don't think he will mind a boundary! Or will he? India will be happy too, to have Hazlewood on strike from the first ball. This is short and outside off, Paine looks to pull. It is a high bumper. It goes off the top edge and to the fine leg fence.
Another dot so once again Paine will need a single from the last ball! on off, this is guided towards point.
On the fuller side, this is pushed towards the man at mid on.
Good length and on middle, Paine defends it onto the ground.
Two again! Shorter and around off, Paine pushes it wide of mid off and takes another couple. Superb batting and these runs would be frustrating India.
Two is the call and two it is! On the pads, this is worked through mid-wicket for a couple.
And he gets the single! Slightly shorter and outside off, Paine manages to hit it wide of point for one. That should never have been a single. The bowler is frustrated and even more so, the skipper.
On off, Paine strokes it nicely to mid off. So Paine has one ball to get a single now.
Close! A leg spinner, it is just outside off. Paine looks to cut but that shot is not on. He is beaten.
Paine now steps out! The length is shortened. It is slapped to covers.
Back of a length and on off, Paine pushes it to covers.
FOUR! Lovely shot! Paine brings out the reverse sweep. He rolls his wrists over the ball to get over the bounce. Plays it nicely all along the ground and to the point fence.
He goes for the short one. Hazlewood stays back and keeps it out.
Just a single as this short ball is pulled nice and hard towards deep square leg. Yorker incoming probably to Hazlewood. Bumrah has one ball to him.
One more dot! Back of a length and on middle, defended.
This one jags back in after landing on off, Paine works it to mid-wicket.
Angled into the off pole, Paine defends it onto the ground.
On middle, this is defended.
Bumrah is back on! 19-7-43-2 for him so far.
A dot to end! On middle, it is blocked once again. So whatever is flat, Hazlewood is blocking and if tossed up, he is going after it. A good over for Australia.
Goes back to bowling it flat and on middle, defended.

FOUR! Chipped over! So the intentions are clear! If it is tossed up, Josh is going to go for it. Ashwin giives it air and lands it on middle, Hazlewood lofts it high and over the mid on fielder for one more boundary.
Tossed up on middle, defended nicely.
FOUR! Vital runs for Australia. Hazlewood is not going to die wondering. This is full and tossed up. Josh goes for it. He hits it hard through mid on for a boundary.
A single from the first ball! Outside off, this is guided through point for one.
Bangs it short to end! Evaded nicely.
Plays one out! On middle, defended.
On middle, this is pushed past the bowler and towards long on for one. So Shami has two balls to bowl to, to Hazlewood.
Good length and on middle, Paine stands tall and blocks it.
Shortish again and on middle, this is worked towards mid-wicket. There is a run on offer but not taken.
Back of a length and on middle, defended.
On middle, Hazlewood manages to keep it out.
Josh Hazlewood walks out to bat!

OUT! TAKEN! Virat looks at the heavens in relief after taking this one. Not sure why though? Probably because India finally hung onto one or they have broken this stand. Could be both too. A soft dismissal. This is on middle. Lyon looks to flick it but does so uppishly. It probably came off slow from the surface. In the end it is chipped to short mid-wicket. Four for Ashwin.
A single now! Paine works this through the leg side and takes one.
Tossed up on middle, it is pushed back to the bowler.
A single now as this is worked towards deep backward square leg.

It lands in no man's land! Not sure how. This is tossed up on off, it turns back in. Lyon looks to sweep but due to the extra bounce. It hits the glove, then the body and lobs near short leg. The fielder there probably did not pick it. Saha runs after it and then dives but fails to get to it.
Clipped away nicely for one! On the pads, this is worked through square leg for a single.
Length and on off, this one does not move, defended easily.
BEATEN! Length and around off, it moves away. Lyon is beaten as he tries to defend it.
Back of a length and on middle, Lyon stays back and keeps it out.
FOUR! Smashed! That is some shot! Shorter, not very short. Lyon jumps onto it and smashes it through mid-wicket.
Back of a length and on off, Lyon stands tall and defends it onto the ground.
On off, blocked.
On the pads, this is worked behind square on the leg side for one.

NOT OUT! There is an inside edge! Lyon brings out the sweep. It this the pad, then the pad and goes towards short fine leg. Ashwin puts in a confident appeal but the umpire shakes his head. After a long chat, Kohli signals the 'T'. Replays roll in and it shows the inside edge.
A huge shout for an LBW has been turned down. India review. Ashwin is pretty confident.
On middle, turning into the batter, Lyon works it down towards fine leg for two.
Tossed up on off, defended.
On the pads, Paine works it through square leg for one.

DRINKS! Paine is doing a good job here! He is scoring some handy runs for Australia. They trail by less than 90 now but they will want to get that down to around 50. Can they do so? India on the other hand, will want to stop that.
Length delivery on off, Paine punches it through point for a single.
BEATEN! Full and outside off, Paine looks to drive but gets misses it.
FOUR! Short delivery outside off, Paine looks to cut but gets an outside edge. It goes over the slip region towards third man for a boundary.
Good length delivery on middle, Paine blocks it off the back foot.
Back of a length on off, Paine keeps it out.

FOUR! 50 for Tim Paine! The skipper leading from the front. He is fighting a lone battle.Has looked the best out of all the Aussie batters. Needs to keep going though. This is shorter and outside off, Paine slashes at it. It goes through backward point for a boundary.

NOT OUT! There is a big inside edge! This is tossed up on off and it turns back in. Lyon looks to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads. Ashwin appeals and the umpire to the surprise of everyone, raises the finger. Lyon reviews and replays show that there is bat. Nathan survives. Good use of the technology.
Review time! Lyon has been given out LBW, he reviews but there is a big inside edge there.
On middle, Lyon keeps it out.
Floated ball on off, Lyon defends it off the back foot.
Flighted delivery on off, Lyon keeps it out.
Floated delivery on off, Paine drives it through mid off for a single.
Tossed up delivery on middle, Paine defends it off the back foot.
Good fielding! This is a full toss on the pads, Lyon flicks it nicely towards leg gully. The fielder dives to his right and stops it.
Outside off again, not played at.
On the pads, this is worked on the leg side for one.
Back of a length and on middle, Tim stands tall and defends it onto the ground.
Angled into the pads, this is worked through the leg side for two.
Good length and on middle, Paine keeps it out.
Gets three! Keeps strike! Down the leg side, Paine plays it smartly as he paddle sweeps it towards fine leg for three.
On off, blocked. The field now comes up. Everybody is in the ring.
Flatter one on off, turning back in. Defended nicely.
On middle, this is worked through mid-wicket for one.
Tossed up on off, defended.
Nathan Lyon is the next batsman in.

OUT! Starc is indeed short. This is the last thing Australia needed, a run out! Not sure if the second run was on or needed there. It is on the pads, Starc works it through square leg and takes one. He calls for a second and goes for it. Shaw gets to the ball and fires it to the keeper. It is a good throw, right beside the stumps and Saha whips the bails off. The umpire takes it upstairs and replays show that Starc is short. Australia still trail by another 105.
A run out appeal has been referred. Starc seems short.
Ravichandran Ashwin is back on.
Length delivery on off, Paine taps it to point.
Full on middle, Paine pushes it to mid on.
BEATEN! Good length ball outside off, Paine looks to defend but misses it.
Full delivery on middle, Paine drives it to mid on.
Good length delivery on off, Paine defends it off the front foot.
Back of a length on middle, Paine flicks it towards fine leg for a couple.

DROPPED! Another one goes down! This one though was a tough. Saha was running backwards and the ball was really swirling. It is short and on middle. Starc looks to pull but gets a top edge. It goes over the keeper who runs back. He is never comfortable under it. He then dives to his left and tries to take it with one hand but spills it. Two taken.
That has missed the off pole by a whisker! A yorker just outside off. Starc maybe expecting a short one is late in getting his bat down. It sneaks under it and just about kisses the off pole.
On the pads, this is worked fine on the leg side for one more.
On middle, it comes in with the angle. Paine plays it to mid-wicket.
Back of a length and on middle, Paine defends it onto the ground.
Angled into the pads, this is worked through square leg for one.
Short again on middle, Starc pulls it over mid-wicket for a single.
Short delivery on middle, Starc looks to pull but gets hit on the shoulder.
Length delivery on off, Paine pushes it through point for a single.
Good length ball on off, Starc looks to defend but gets an outside edge. It goes towards gully. The batsmen get three runs.
Back of a length on off, Starc keeps it out.
Good length delivery on off, Paine pushes it towards covers for a quick single.
On the pads, this is nudged down fine towards the fine leg fielder for one more.
On the pads, this is worked fine on the leg side for two.
On off, this one stays a touch low. It goes off the bottom part towards mid on for one.

Short of a length and on off, Wade pushes this one towards point. Wade says no run straightaway. The communication between these two has been good so far.
Outside off, Matthew does not want to have a poke at this one.
Full on middle, tucked to short mid-wicket. A good over from Shami. Just 2 runs.
On off, pushed towards the man at mid on.
On a good length on off, Burns pushes this to point.
On off, pushed towards covers.
Full on middle, worked through square leg for a brace.
Good length ball on off, defended to the leg side.
On off, pushed to point.
Short of a length on middle, Wade looks to evade it but does not completely as the ball hits his back. That would have stung.
Back of a length and on off, Wade pushes it to the off side.
Outside off, left alone.
Short ball on off, Wade pulls but it comes off the lower part of the blade and goes to the man at square leg.
On off, pushed to the leg side.
Full and around off, pushed to mid on.
Outside off, left alone.
LEG BYE! On the pads, Wade tickles it towards fine leg for one. The umpire signals this as a leg bye.

A tame appeal for LBW but turned down. A back of a length ball on off and middle, Wade looks to play at this but misses to get hit high on the pads. The players appeal but no says the umpire. Height could have been an issue there.
Full and around off, Burns pushes this to the off side and takes a quick run.
Burns is a typical Test match player. You keep bowling length balls outside off and he makes a leave.
A dot to end! Wade comes on the front foot and then shoulders arms to this length ball outside off.
Now Wade does not play at this length ball which is way outside off.
On a length and around off, Wade taps it to cover-point and calls a loud 'no run' to his partner.
Full and around off, Wade strokes it to the man at covers.
Length and outside off, Wade does not fiddle with it.
Length ball angled into off, Wade blocks it to the leg side.
Length and outside off, Burns lets it be.

That was nasty! Short and aimed at the batsman, Burns lines up for the pull but then decides to let it go through. Though he is late on it as the ball takes the chest, then the grille and lobs towards the slip cordon. The fielders claim a catch but nothing from the umpire and India too do not review.
Another length ball outside off and Burns makes another leave.
Length delivery outside off, Burns makes a leave this time. With the new ball, you need to make the batsmen play.
BURNS IS ALSO UP AND RUNNING! Full and slanting on the pads, Burns flicks it towards deep square leg and takes a brace to open his account.
On a length and around off, Wade taps it towards short cover and takes a quick single.
Outside off, left alone. Burns has faced 13 balls but has still not opened his account.
On the pads, tucked towards fine leg for a single.
FOUR! Wade and Australia open their account in some fashion! A back of a length ball outside off, width offered to Wade, he punches this one through the cover region for a boundary.
On middle, blocked out.
Back of a length ball on middle, Wade fends this one out. Says no run instantly. Australia still have not opened their account in this innings.
On the body, no space awarded to Wade, he looks to push this to the on side but misses to get hit on the body.
Yes, a dot on the last ball will mean that this is the fourth maiden in a row for India. A length ball outside off, Burns does not have a poke at this.
Outside off, Burns does not engage at this one too. Fourth maiden in a row incoming?
Short of a length outside off, Joe raIses his blade and lets this one pass to Saha.
On off, pushed towards mid on.
Outside off, left alone.
EDGY! Short of a length on off, Burns looks to defend but it takes the outside edge and goes towards gully.
Three maidens in a row! Back of a length on middle, Wade looks to fend it away but misses to get hit high on the thigh pad. A good start by Umesh.
Another ball which is behind the good length on off, tapped towards point. Wade says 'NO RUNNN' straightaway.
Outside off, Wade has no issues in leaving this one alone.
Back of a length ball on off, Wade nudges this to the leg side.
Short of a length on middle, Wade looks to tuck it to the leg side but misses to get hit high on the thigh pad.
BEATEN! Good delivery from Umesh! On a good length on off, Wade looks to block this one out but the ball whizzes past the outside edge into the mitts of Saha.
A maiden for Bumrah too! Length and around off, Burns shoulders arms to it.
On a length and around off, Joe blocks it with soft hands and right under his eyes.
Now Bumrah bowls it very wide of off stump, Burns won't play at it.
SO CLOSE TO THE EDGE! Bumrah bowls one on a length and around off, the ball just about nips away as Burns has a tentative poke at it. The ball though sneaks past the outside edge.
Another length ball in that channel outside off, Burns is happy to leave it.
Length ball outside off, Burns makes a leave.
Who will it be with the ball partnering Yadav? It will be Jasprit Bumrah.
A dot to end! A maiden from Umesh! Full and wide outside off, Matthew is happy to let that pass.
Length and outside off, Wade makes a leave this time.
Wade is being too tentative here. Another length ball around off, Wade once again goes chasing the ball but is lucky not to edge it behind.

We are all in readiness to begin the Australian batting for the first innings. Their openers, Joe Burns and Matthew Wade stride out into the middle. The players of India are in a huddle and Virat Kohli is imparting some final words of wisdom before the players spread out to their respective positions. Umesh Yadav with the ball first up for India.
BEATEN! Another length ball that leaves the left hander there, Wade looks to have a poke at it but fails to lay bat on ball. It misses the outside edge this time once again.
Length ball around off, Wade makes a leave now.
Nice start from Yadav! Pitches it in the channel around off, Wade looks to push it to the off side but gets beaten.
So the target for Australia is 90 runs. Can they do it today itself? We will soon find out on the other side of this short break.

The bowling from the Aussies was just brilliant. Tim Paine with his fielding placements was spot on. Though Pat Cummins started the procession but it was Josh Hazlewood who stole the show with his 5-fer. Cummins ended with a 4-fer too as Starc played a perfect foil to them. Only three bowlers were required by Australia to skittle out India cheaply.

The day began with the two overnight batsman occupying the crease for India but what unfolded was sheer brilliance from the Aussies. The departure of Bumrah opened the floodgates as wickets started falling in a heap. None of the Indian batters managed to get to double figures. A sad story for any Indian fan but this is reality. Pujara and Rahane departed without troubling the scorers as Kohli was out due to the sheer brilliance from Cameron Green. All in all a poor batting display.

Ohh! A bit of concern for India as the players walk off. Shami looks to be in some pain and is not in a state to continue. That ends the innings for India too. They are 36/9 and lead by 89 runs. Looks serious though but nevertheless, Australia would be a happy bunch of players after their fiery display with the ball.

The physio is out there to have a look at Shami. Some magic spray being applied and some running repairs done on him. He though seems to be fine to continue. Ohh! Hang on he as asked for the physio once again. He looks to be in some pain and is thus feeling uncomfortable.

OOUCHHH! That must have pinged Shami hard! Much short and following the batsman there, Shami looks to go towards the leg side but the ball hurries onto him as he gets in a tangle there. In the end, the ball hits his wrists and drops onto the pitch.
Short and down the leg side, Shami looks to help it on its way to fine leg but fails to get anything behind that shot.
Length delivery on off, Yadav keeps it out.
FOUR! Lucky runs there for India! Short delivery on middle, Umesh Yadav looks to pull but gets a top edge. It goes towards fine leg for a boundary.
Length delivery on off, Yadav defends it off the back foot.
Back of a length on middle, Shami flicks it towards mid-wicket for a single.
Good length delivery on off, Shami defends it off the back foot.
Mohammed Shami is the last man in.

OUT! CAUGHT! 9 down are India! A lead of 84 runs is what they have. What is happening here. Hazlewood gets a 5-fer. What a time to get to it. Josh bowls it around off, and gets it to nip away from Vihari. Hanuma who looks to have a feel for the ball can only manage to get a thick outside edge which is gobbled up by the keeper who goes to his right and pouches it.
Full delivery on middle, Yadav looks to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Back of a length on middle, Vihari pushes it towards mid-wicket for a single.
Back of a length on off, Vihari defends it off the back foot.
Length ball on off, Vihari keeps it out.
FOUR! Nicely played! Length delivery outside off, Vihari punches it through point for a boundary.
Good length delivery on off, Vihari defends it off the back foot.
No Hat-Trick for Hazlewood but he gets to another milestone of 200 Test scalps for Australia. Length and around off, Yadav hangs on the back foot and keeps it out.
Umesh Yadav is the new batsman in. He will face the Hat-Trick ball from Hazlewood!

OUT! CAUGHT! Australia into the Indian tail now with this wicket! Brilliant from Josh there. He bowls one around off and Ashwin who is caught on the back foot within the crease can only manage to get a faint tickle behind to the keeper. Tim Paine there takes the catch and goes up in an appeal joined by his bowler. The umpire too raises his finger after the appeal. Ashwin though is not convinced and challenges the decision taking it to third umpire. Replays roll in and it is a legal delivery as we move to HotSpot but nothing  on it though. Now we move to RTS and there is a spike as the ball goes past the outside edge. Keep walking Ashwin there.

An appeal for caught behind is taken upstairs. Ashwin is adjudged out but he takes the help of the third umpire here. Lets's see what the replays have to show. It is a legal delivery as HotSpot comes on but nothing on it as we move to Real Time Snicko. Oh! There is a spike there and Ashwin you boy keep on walking there.
Ravichandran Ashwin is the new batsman in.

OUT! CAUGHT! India cannot getting anything at the moment. Yes, they are only getting casuality right now. Josh bowls one on a length and around middle and leg, Saha goes for the flick but does not bother to keep it down as he hits it uppishly. The ball goes straight to short mid-wicket where Marnus Labuschagne is stationed, he accepts it gleefully and India lose their 7th.
Short and around off, Saha sways away from the line this time.
Good length and around off, Saha plays the forward block on this one.
Length and around middle, Saha keeps it out.
DRINKS! The hour on Day 3 has so far belonged to Australia as they have scapled 5 wickets and put India under all sorts of pressure. Cummins started it and then Hazlewood took over from him.
Length and angled into the pads, Vihari keeps it out off the back foot towards the leg side.
Outside off, left alone by Vihari.
On a length and around off, Vihari keeps it out off the back foot.
Exquisite! Fuller and around off, Vihari punches the ball off the front foot but does not have enough on the shot to clear the fence. The batters take a couple though.
Short of a length ball on off, Vihari taps it to covers and shouts a loud 'no' to his partner.
Length and outside off, left alone by Vihari.
Full and around middle, Saha flicks it past the short leg fielder and towards mid-wicket for a couple of runs.
Bowls a hard length this time does Hazlewood and Saha lifts his bat to let the ball pass through.
Good length and around off, Saha blocks it off the front foot with the full face of the bat.
Full and on the pads, Vihari strokes it towards mid on and takes a quick single as the fielder there misses his shy at the bowler's end.
Short and wide outside off, Vihari looks to go with the cut but the ball bounces a bit extra and goes past the outside edge
Short of good length and around off, Vihari defends it off the front foot.
Full on middle, Saha looks to flick but gets a leading edge. It lands safely towards mid off.
Length delivery outside off, Saha leaves it alone.
BEATEN! Short ball outside off, Saha looks to defend but misses it.
Good length delivery on off, Saha looks to leave but gets it off the toe end of the bat. It goes towards fine leg. The batsmen get two runs.
Short delivery outside off, Saha sways away from it.
BEATEN! Good length ball outside off, Vihari looks to defend but misses it.
Back of a length on off, Vihari keeps it out.
Length delivery on off, Vihari defends it off the back foot.
Good length ball on middle, Vihari looks to defend but gets hit on the thigh pad.
Length delivery on middle, Vihari looks to defend but misses it and gets hit on the pads.
BEATEN! Good length ball outside off, Vihari looks to defend but misses it.
Back of a length outside off, Vihari shoulders arms to this one.
Another length ball on the stumps, Saha keeps it out.
Short of good length and around off, Saha blocks it off the back foot.
Wriddiman Saha is the new batsman in.

OUT! CAUGHT! Brilliant effort in the field from the debutant Cameron Green! Pat gets his 4th wicket and he is on fire here. Bowls one on a length and around off, how many times have we seen Kohli chase a wide delivery in Test cricket? The answer would be many times. The nemesis of 2014 England tour comes to the fore. Pat Cummins did the same thing here. He bowls it on a length and outside off, Kohli trying to break the shackles looks to take the bowler on but ends up chipping it uppishly to the man at point where Green dives to his left and goes for the catch. He though does not take it on the first attempt but manages to hold onto it on the rebounce. Kohli though stands there as the umpire takes it upstairs to check whether the catch is clean or not. The soft signal is out and after multiple replays the third umpire deems it to be a clean take and Kohli has to walk back. India in dire straits.

The third umpire is called for fair catch. The soft signal is OUT. Looks to be clean from one angle but the third umpire is having a closer look there. Has he taken the catch cleanly. Looks to be so. Yes, the big screen shows OUT. Kohli takes a walk back for one last time with the bat on this tour.
FOUR! EDGY but India will take it. Length and outside off, Kohli plays it through gully and gets a boundary at third man.
Length and outside off, Kohli lets it be.
Good length and around off, Kohli plays it to gully.
Length and outside off, Vihari lets it be. A double wicket maiden from Hazlewood comes to an end.
Hanuma Vihari is the next batsman in.

OUT! CAUGHT! Another one bites the dust! Rahane departs for a duck! India in all sorts of trouble here. From 6/1 they are 15/5 in no time. Hazlewood bowls a fuller one this time in that channel around off, Rahane goes for the defensive push with hard hands but ends up getting a thick outside edge behind to the keeper who accepts it gleefully.
BEATEN! Bounce and pace on this one! Length and around off, Hazlewood gets it to shape a bit away as Rahane goes to feel the ball.
Length and outside off, Rahane shoulders arms to it. The captain and his deputy out in the middle.
Good length and around off, Rahane blocks it off the front foot here.
Ajinkya Rahane is the new batsman in.

OUT! CAUGHT! Perfect from Hazlewood. Bowls it on a good length and around off, Agarwal does the same mistake as that of Pujara as he too goes to defend off the back foot. The ball just about shapes away from the batsman to catch the outside edge. This time though it goes at a good height to Paine who takes it with ease. Looks like India are losing the plot here.
Length and around middle, Kohli turns this one to short leg where Travis Head does well to field it. A wicket maiden for Cummins.
Beauty! Length and around off, angled into Kohli, Virat looks to defend it but is lucky to not have got an edge on it.
Length and outside off, Kohli makes a leave.
Short of length on off, Kohli keeps it out.
Virat Kohli is the next batsman in.

OUT! CAUGHT! Cummins strikes once again! Pujara departs! Excellent from Pat there. He keeps bowling in that channel outside off and gets this one to come a bit inward and then takes it away from the batter. Pujara who is caught on the crease fails to get to the pitch of the ball as he pokes it tentatively. The ball though kisses the outside edge and goes low towards Tim Paine where he does well to go low and take it.
Length and outside off, Pujara does well to cover his off pole and lets it be.
A bit squared up there! Good length and full of pace, Agarwal who is camping on the back foot to defend is hurried into the shot but does well to play with soft hands as he gets a bit squared up too.
Bumper! Short and around middle, Agarwal ducks quickly to let the ball go through.
Short of good length ball rising after pitching, Agarwal does well to get his bat inside the line and let the ball go through into the mitts of the keeper.
Short of good length and around off, Agarwal defends it off the back foot towards cover-point this time.
Good length and around off, Agarwal blocks it off the back foot towards gully.
Length and way outside off, Agarwal sees the line and then lifts his willow to allow safe passage for the ball.
Length and outside off, Pujara is not at all going to go after them as he makes a leave. A maiden from Pat too.
Good length and around off, Pujara is happy to keep it out off the back foot this time.
Short and around off, Pujara sees it and does well to drop his wrists as he sways away from the line of the ball.
Solid block! Length and around off, Pujara comes on the front foot and defends it with the full face of the bat to the off side.
Fuller and around off, Pujara turns it to mid on this time off the front foot.
Short of good length and outside off, Pujara keeps it out off the back foot towards point.
Short of good length and around off, Agarwal strokes it to mid off this time. A maiden from Starc.
Full and around off, Agarwal taps it to cover-point off the front foot.
Short delivery in line with the middle and leg stump, Agarwal does well to duck under it.
Fuller and around off, Agarwal strokes it straight to the man at short covers this time.
Good length delivery outside off, Mayank shoulders arms to it.
Length and around off, Agarwal keeps it out off the back foot now.
Cheteshwar Pujara is the new batsman in.

OUT! CAUGHT AND BOWLED! Cummins strikes! Brilliant change of pace there. Bowls a fuller length ball around off but also ensures to take the pace of the ball. Bumrah looks to defend it off the front foot but is early into the shot as the ball lobs off the higher part of the bat towards Cummins. Patto there gets to the ball and gobbles it up with ease.
Cummins tries the bumper and Bumrah is equally smart to sway away from the line of the delivery.
Good length and around off, Bumrah looks to have a tentative poke but is lucky not to get the edge there.
Back of a length ball around off from Cummins, Bumrah stands tall and keeps it out once again from within the crease.
Length and around off, Bumrah blocks it off the back foot this time.

In the air... but in the gap! Fuller and around off, Bumrah looks to drive it through covers but gets it a bit squarer and gets it through the gap between cover-point. The batters in the meanwhile get a couple of runs.
Pat Cummins to bowl from the other end.
Full and outside off, Agarwal leaves it alone.
Length ball outside off, Agarwal watches it and then decides to make a leave.
FOUR! First runs of the day. Starc strays one on the pads and Agarwal handsomely flicks it through square leg and gets a boundary. Brilliant stuff from him there.
Length and outside off, Agarwal lets it be.
Beaten! Length and angled across the right hander, Agarwal goes chasing after it but is lucky not to edge that to the keeper.

Starc right on the money! A huge shout but nothing from the umpire. Mitchell lands one on a length and gets it to nip back in. Agarwal who prods forward to defend gets an inside edge onto the pads. Starc appeals but nothing from the umpire.

We are all set to begin the action on Day 3. The two Indian batsmen Mayank Agarwal and nightwatchman Jasprit Bumrah are out in the middle. The Australian team after taking a piece of advice from their skipper, Tim Paine disperse onto the field. Mitchell Starc will start the proceedings for Day 3. 3-1-3-0 are his figures so far.

Hello and welcome one and all for Day 3 of the Pink Ball Test between India and Australia. Day 3 often referred as the moving day in Test cricket is a day which decides what will be the outcome of the Test. Will we see similar things here too? Will we get to know in who's grasp is the game going? India with a lead of 62 runs and 9 wickets in hand will look to amass as much as possible to bat Australia out of the game. Whereas, Australia would look to chip in with quick wickets to halt the Indian caravan from running away with the game. Who will come out on top? We will soon find out as the day gets going.
... Day 3, Session 1 ...

On we move to Day 3. The first couple of hours should decide the course of this game. If Australia manage to take wickets regularly, they will be in this game. If India do not lose more than 2 wickets and get more than 60-70 runs in the afternoon session, it would mean that they are effectively 130-140 for 3 from where, they can dictate terms and shut the hosts out of this match. Join us for all the action from 2.30 pm local (0400 GMT). ADIOS! TAKE CARE!

Life is tough. So is cricket. This is what Prithvi Shaw would be feeling. With every forward press from Bumrah, actually invoking applause from everyone in the dressing room of India, Shaw would be gutted for having missed out on this match, which might also be his last, given his returns and the demand to get in Shubman Gill. India could have easily been 2 down but Mayank Agarwal lives to fight on Saturday. A tense passage of play, with the score reading 9/1 but overall, in terms of the game situation, India are well-placed, effectively being 62/1.

A day which was not kind to batsmen. 15 wickets fell overall, for just 209 runs, in roughly 80 overs. A day of attrition, felt largely by Australia because after all the hard work put in by their bowlers on Day 1, they put up a really average batting display. In a timid approach, one can say, where the batsmen hardly tried to score, the wickets eventually went to the Indian bowlers and in spite of losing an early wicket, they will believe they are in the driver's seat.

This Test match has picked up frenetic pace. We are already into the third innings even before finishing Day 2. On a normal Test wicket, this seems like an evenly-poised match, but in this scenario, India are way ahead.
On a length, outside off, Bumrah leaves it for Paine to collect. STUMPS ON DAY 2, INDIA LEAD BY 62!
Slower ball, fuller in length, pretty straight, kept out again.
A wayward bouncer, down the leg side, Jasprit ducks. Just 2 more balls to get through.
Very full, outside off, a solid, solid defense from Boom Boom.
Around off, Bumrah works it behind square leg, sets off for the single but is sent back! Rightly so. Bumrah is out there to protect the batsman.
Full and around off, watchfully defended.
Full and outside off, nice confident push from Agarwal through the covers for a couple. Starc is done for the day.
Perfect yorker, around off, swinging in, but equally well dug out.
On a length, outside off, angling away, shouldered arms to.
Misfired, down the leg side. MA looks to flick but misses.
This is on the stumps, curving back in. Mayank works it to the leg side but Travis Head at short leg intercepts it well.
On a length, around off, Agarwal shoulders arms.
Outside off, well negotiated by Boom Boom, as he pushes this towards point.
A short ball, around off, JB ducks,
Back to bowling it full, Jasprit defends it solidly.
This is on a length, outside off, Boom Boom happily sways away.
A good ball to a new batsman, full and straight, but Bumrah defends it watchfully.
Will we see a night watchman? Yes. It is Boom Boom Jasprit Bumrah.

OUT! CLEANED HIM UP! If Mitch doesn't get you, Pat will. And Pat deserves a pat on his back. He could have been frustrated after a very trying first over but he eventually gets one of the openers. Pretty much similar to the way Starc got Shaw on Thursday. A length ball, outside off, Shaw looks to defend but there is a big gap between his bat and pad. The naughty ball exposes that gap. Does just enough to get back in, go through the gap, perhaps take a tiny little inside edge and shatter the woodwork behind.
This is outside off again, on a length, comes back in a little but Agarwal knows where his off stump is and shoulders arms.
Outside off, angling away, let through.

Lovely ball. On a length, outside off, swinging back in, Mayank looks to defend but misses and is hit on the pads. The entire slip cordon goes up in an appeal but Starc has his hands on his head. He spotted the inside edge.

IN THE AIR... DOES NOT CARRY! Everyone is nervy out there. Full and outside off, Agarwal goes at this with hard hands, looking to push. But the ball barely comes off the surface. Flies off the face of the bat but lands well short of Matthew Wade at short extra cover, rushing to his right. He slips as well.
On a length now, around off, pushed towards mid on.
Outside off, on a length, left alone.

EDGED BUT DROPPED! It is captain Paine who has no one else to blame. Cummins finally gets it right, landing it on a length outside off and getting it to move away. Agarwal feels for it, looking to push but only manages a thick outside edge, due to the late movement. It dips on its way behind, between the keeper and first slip. Tim Paine dives to his right but cannot quite make it stick in his glove. Would that have carried to first slip? Guess it might have.
On a length, outside off, watchfully pushed towards point.
Goes for the yorker, does Cummins, but dishes out a low full toss. Perhaps trying a little bit too hard. Agarwal works it through mid-wicket for a couple.
Around off, on a length, helped in front of short leg.

That is a real confident push from Prithvi Shaw. Overpitched from Cummins, on middle and off, Shaw just times this back past the bowler. However, the ball stops before the ropes and mid off gets to it. Three runs taken.
A length ball, around off, worked wide of mid on but it is stopped.
Pat Cummins to bowl from the other end.
Good leave to end the over. MA has left a ball on off stump, but it is short enough. Not a great opening over from Starc.
That's the ball. Starc gets this to start from off stump and then shape back in, but Mayank is solid in blocking it to the leg side.
Doing too much. Starc finally gets the ball to swing. But it starts from middle and is comfortably going down, as it hits Agarwal's pads when he misses his flick.
Fuller and wider outside off, easily left alone. India will not mind this line.
Around off, angling away, steered towards gully.
Relief for Shaw. A length ball, but outside leg, helped to fine leg to get off the mark and the pair.

That's it from this Pink Ball Test as Australia win comprehensively to lead the 4-match series 1-0. Virat Kohli goes home for the birth of his first child as Ajinkya Rahane takes over the mantle from him. Will a change in leadership bring a change in team India's fortunes? We will soon find out as the 2nd Test starts on the Boxing Day i.e 26th of December 2020. That game begins at 1030 local (2330 GMT, Previous Day). Till then, enjoy your Christmas, stay safe, take care and cheers.

Virat Kohli, India skipper, says that it is hard to find words to express and to lose from a lead of 53 runs is something we did not expect. He further, says that we did not take the morning session too well as they went hard at the ball. He goes onto mention that the Australian bowlers put them in situations where the edges were found but he says that there was nothing in the pitch which could be termed as drastic. Wishes his team for the remainder of the series and hopes that they come out stronger. On Mohammed Shami, he tells that right now he is going for a scan and then a decision would be made but mentions that he was in a lot of pain.

Australia skipper and Man of the Match, Tim Paine, says that he just asked his bowlers that they have the ability to take quick wickets and they just go out and try and exploit anything there on the surface. He further says that it is nice to get off to a good start but reckons that the first innings batting was poor. On Joe Burns, he says that it feels good to have him back in the runs as that gives stability to the team. On his own batting, he says that this was due for a long time and in the end, contributing to the team's success is what they strive for.

India's second innings was just like a haunted nightmare where there were ruins. They lost Shaw once again cheaply on Day 2 and when they resumed their innings on the morning of Day 3 what unfolded was sheer hara-kiri. Pat Cummins started the downfall for India when he sent Jasprit Bumrah packing but then Hazlewood came in with a lot of Josh (steam) to topple India's best in business with his precision bowling. In the end, India folded up for a paltry 36 runs on board in their second essay with the bat. For Australia it was just three bowlers who did the job for them, Cummins and Starc began the day but the star with the ball was Josh Hazlewood who ripped apart the Indian batting with a 5-wicket haul, his 8th in the format and also went past 200 Test wickets. In the end, Australia chased the target of 90 runs with ease to take a lead of 1-0 in the 4-match Test series. Don't go anywhere as we bring you the post-match presentations...

Australia's first innings also was no different from India. They too lost their top order cheaply and barring Marnus Labuschagne's 47 and Tim Paine's 73 none of the batters got going as they folded for 191 runs, conceding a lead of 53 in the process. For India, Ravichandran Ashwin was the pick of the lot as he ended with a 4-fer. The next best was Umesh Yadav who had 3 wickets to his name and Bumrah managed to get a couple too.

Earlier after winning the toss, India went onto post 244 runs in their first innings. The star with the bat then was Virat Kohli who stroked to a well compiled 74 before being run out. The others to contribute substantially were Cheteshwar Pujara and Ajinkya Rahane who both contributed by scoring around 40 odd runs. Rest all the batters failed to get themselves in. On the Australian bowling, Starc was the pick of the bowlers as he ended with 4 wickets to his name. Cummins ended with 3 wickets as Hazlewood and Lyon ended with a wicket each. The debutant Cameron Green though went wicketless.

Chasing a target of 90 never looked to be a daunting one as the two Australian openers started their quest towards victory. Though, Burns began watchfully, as Wade was right into the 4th gear as he found the fence quite often. After the dinner break, Burns too joined the party, as the duo went onto score runs at will and in competition as well as in the company of each other they stitched a stand worth 70 runs. Though Wade departed followed by Marnus Labuschagne. Joe Burns though kept his cool and hit the winning runs as well as brought up his fifty too. There was nothing in India's bowling in the second innings of Australia as they sprayed all around and were hit for runs. Also, with fewer runs to defend and a bowler short they were under a lot of pressure. Only Ashwin got a wicket and was the one because of whom Wade was run out. All-in-all the day belonged to Australia.

A thumping win for Australia here in the first Border-Gavaskar Test. A complete performance from their bowlers and batsmen. A humiliating loss for India though who were just blown away in their second innings.

Do join us for the second session which could well turn out to be the final one of this game as Australia need another 75 runs to win. Can they do it? Or will India spring up a surprise here? All answers coming up on the other side of the break.

In the short period what Australia got to bat in the 4th innings they have added 15 runs without losing a wicket as they chase 90 for a win in the first Test. The bowling so far has been wayward from Yadav though Bumrah has been good in patches. The loss of Shami with the ball would hurt India and it remains to be seen how India manage their bowling resources in this game with a bowler short.

Australia's bowling was just brilliant on the day. Pat Cummins, Mitchell Starc and Josh Hazlewood were the three bowlers used by Australia in India's second innings. Cummins and Hazlewood wrecked havoc in the Indian camp as they shared 8 wickets between them. In the process, Cummins went past 150 Test wickets and Hazlewood went past 200 Test wickets. All in all a top class display of fast bowling from the Aussie duo as Starc played a perfect foil for them.

What an amazing session we have had. Test cricket lives upto its charm. Resuming on their overnight score of 7/1, India soon found themselves in deep waters when they were reduced to 15/5. None of the batsmen looked to adjust to the conditions as they kept on coming and going away. None of them managed to get to even double digits as Pujara and  Rahane went without scoring. Shami though got injured and helped India avoid the blushes of getting out for a paltry 36 in their second innings.
